'''Highfield College''' was an [[Independent school|independent]], [[Day school|day]] and [[boarding school]] for boys, in [[Turramurra, New South Wales|Turramurra]], on the [[North Shore (Sydney)|North Shore]] of [[Sydney]], New South Wales, Australia.

==History==
The school was opened in 1907<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article103248774 |title=Australian Wines. |newspaper=[[The_Newsletter:_an_Australian_Paper_for_Australian_People|The Newsletter: an Australian Paper for Australian People (Sydney, NSW : 1900 - 1918)]] |location=Sydney, NSW |date=6 April 1907 |accessdate=30 April 2014 |page=9 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> at 51 Ku-ring-gai Avenue, Turramurra, in a house owned by William John Baker. The property was rented by the Redgrave family and [[Leslie Alfred Redgrave]] was the proprietor and headmaster of the school. His brother Wilfred Harold ran the junior school. Advertising for the school said:<br>(a) An Ideal Home for Young Boys, with a mother's care, and best of food, and every comfort.<br>(b) Primary and Secondary Education, with the Individual Attention of Graduate Masters.<br>(c) Specially equipped Classrooms, Dormitories, and playing Fields, in a fine healthy climate.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article14868404 |title=Advertising. |newspaper=[[Sydney Morning Herald|The Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)]] |location=NSW |date=22 June 1907 |accessdate=30 April 2014 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>On its closure in 1915 the building was demolished and redeveloped with a new home in 1917.<ref>[http://www.khs.org.au/historian_database/qr.html The Historian Vol. 31 No 1, March 2002 by Jennifer Harvey and Lois McEvoy ''About No 51''] Retrieved 30 April 2014</ref>

==Notable alumni==
* [[Frank Nicklin|Sir George Francis Reuben Nicklin]], {{post-nominals|country=AUS|KCMG,|MM}}, [[Premier of Queensland|Premier]] of [[Queensland]] from 1957 to 1968<ref>[http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/nicklin-sir-george-francis-frank-11237/text20039 Sir George Francis (Frank) Nicklin, Australian Dictionary of Biography] Retrieved 30 April 2014.</ref>

